ExplanationOfAllophones: [i] in word-initial positions and after palatalized consonants.
[ɨ] after non-palatalized consonants.

Normally [i] under primary or secondary stress. If the word contains more than one instance of the same vowel phoneme, their quality changes between closed and half-open in accordance with the stress alternation. The particular class of consonants then determines whether the quality alternation starts from closed or from half-open. If the preceding consonant is of the acute class (s, t, n, ɲ) , the stressed /i/ is closed [i]. The following syllable would be half-open [ɪ], a further /i/ would come under secondary stress and again be closed, etc.
If, on the other hand, the preceding consonant is of the grave class (k, kʷ q, p, ʔ), the stressed /i/ is half-open [ɪ], an /i/ in the following, unstressed syllable would be closed [i], etc.
Word final instances are always open if the word is not monosyllabic.

Normally [i] under primary or secondary stress. If the word contains more than one instance of the same vowel phoneme, their quality changes between closed and half-open in accordance with the stress alternation. The particular class of consonants then determines whether the quality alternation starts from closed or from half-open. If the preceding consonant is of the acute class (s, t, n, ɲ) , the stressed /i/ is closed [i]. The following syllable would be half-open [ɪ], a further /i/ would come under secondary stress and again be closed, etc.
If, on the other hand, the preceding consonant is of the grave class (k, kʷ q, p, ʔ), the stressed /i/ is half-open [ɪ], an /i/ in the following, unstressed syllable would be closed [i], etc.

The allophones of /u/ show a distribution exactly parallel: closed [u] under stress after acute consonants, half-open [ʊ] under stress after grave consonants.
Word final instances are always open if the word is not monosyllabic.

The behavior of the /e/ allophones is not exactly parallel and is altogether not too clear. Some examples seem to conform to the rules as formulated above for /i/ and /u/.

If the word contains more than one /a/-sound, the mid and back variants are conditioned by the stress alternation in a way parallel to the distribution of closed and half-open variants of the high and mid vowels: back [ɒ] occurs under stress, mid [a] in unstressed position.
